core.conflict

Interface IConflictCandidate<T,E>

  • Type Parameters:
    T - The type of the conflict candidate entity (the same type of the entities that define the conflict scope for this conflict candidate entity).
    E - The type of entities that underly the conflict arising by the conflict source entity of the conflict scope for this conflict candidate entity.
    All Known Subinterfaces:
    IConflictSource<T,E>
    All Known Implementing Classes:
    AbstractConflictCandidate, AbstractConflictSource, GeneralizationAdaptationClassAssociationClassConflictCandidate, GeneralizationAdaptationClassAssociationConflictCandidate, GeneralizationAdaptationClassAttributeConflictCandidate, GeneralizationAdaptationClassDependencyConflictCandidate, OwningClassAssociationConflictSource, OwningClassAttributeConflictSource, OwningClassDependencyConflictSource

    public interface IConflictCandidate<T,E>
    an IConflictCandidate generic interface that defines a conflict candidate entity.

    This interface provides operations for accessing/setting a conflict candidate's underlying entity, and an operation to verify if it satisfies a conflict predicate. If it does then it can be considered as a conflict source entity for a conflict scope within a conflict domain.

    All entities having the same type as that of entities defining a conflict scope for a conflict domain, are conflict candidates for this domain, and for the conflict scope in particular. A conflict candidate entity has to fulfill a conflict predicate in order to be considered as a conflict source entity. A conflict candidate entity might require having access to information provided by both the conflict domain entity and its conflict scope.

    It must be implemented by any concrete class designating a conflict candidate.
    Author:
    Bachar Rima
    See Also:
    IConflictDomain, AbstractConflictScope, AbstractConflictCandidate
